<div id="review_2748365445" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2748365445" />
    <a title="Florencia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/21575078-florencia"><img alt="Florencia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1624565478p2/21575078.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2748365445?book_show_action=true">Mar 12, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Florencia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Florencia" href="/user/show/21575078-florencia">Florencia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780146000959" href="/book/show/1158916.The_Rubai_yat_of_Omar_Khayyam">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21575078-florencia?shelf=middle-east">middle-east</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/21575078-florencia?shelf=poetry">poetry</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2748365445" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2452421799962074615"><blockquote>What is most vital is that Fitzgerald completely misconstrued the meaning of the Persian mystic. He regarded Khayaam’s poem as a statement of hedonism and atheism… Graves discloses, on the contrary, that the poem expresses profound religious faith. Perhaps Fitzgerald lacked sufficient knowledge of Persian. Perhaps the symbolism of the Rubaiyyat simply eluded him.</blockquote><br/>Excerpt from the <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1538844.The_Original_Rubaiyyat_of_Omar_Khayaam' rel='nofollow noopener'>&quot;original&quot;</a> Rubaiyyat which isn&apos;t original at all and perhaps that is the only truth it contains, who knows. Apparently</span>
  <span id="freeText2452421799962074615" style="display:none"><blockquote>What is most vital is that Fitzgerald completely misconstrued the meaning of the Persian mystic. He regarded Khayaam’s poem as a statement of hedonism and atheism… Graves discloses, on the contrary, that the poem expresses profound religious faith. Perhaps Fitzgerald lacked sufficient knowledge of Persian. Perhaps the symbolism of the Rubaiyyat simply eluded him.</blockquote><br />Excerpt from the <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1538844.The_Original_Rubaiyyat_of_Omar_Khayaam" rel="nofollow noopener">"original"</a> Rubaiyyat which isn't original at all and perhaps that is the only truth it contains, who knows. Apparently, Edward FitzGerald took many liberties and his translation - the first one of this poem - resulted in a very different book. Bad news for me as FitzGerald’s work sounds more appealing, albeit completely unreal. In any case, since Robert Graves' book would be a waste of time, I have two versions to read: FitzGerald and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/1028019.The_Ruba_iyat_of_Omar_Khayyam" rel="nofollow noopener">Peter Avery's</a>, maybe the real poem? (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/441200.Eugene_Onegin_A_Novel_in_Verse" rel="nofollow noopener">Eugene Onegin</a> flashbacks.)<br /><br />March 31, 19<br /><br />*<br /><br />I've read this without being able to stop thinking: this is not what Khayyám wrote. A shame.<br /><br /><blockquote><b>LII</b><br />And that inverted Bowl we call The Sky,<br />Whereunder crawling coop't we live and die,<br />Lift not thy hands to It for help - for It<br />Rolls impotently on as Thou or I.</blockquote><br /><br />April 2, 19<br />* Later on <a href="https://nonbookreviews.wordpress.com/" rel="nofollow noopener">my blog</a>.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2452421799962074615" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


