<div id="review_29874835" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/29874835" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1287856-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442489432p2/1287856.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/29874835?book_show_action=true">Aug 11, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/1287856-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9781596054387" href="/book/show/405765.The_Rubaiyat_of_Omar_Khayyam_First_Second_and_Fifth_Editions">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1287856-david?shelf=pomez">pomez</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer29874835" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7063093206740765355">Some poetry snobs find these verses corny, with their psuedo-archaism of langauge and what nowadays would be called Orientalist romanticism.<br/><br/>To Hell with all that. I&apos;ve always liked them. In fact, I memorized most of it when I was a kid.<br/><br/>&quot;The moving Finger writes, and having writ, <br/>Moves on, nor all your Piety nor Wit<br/>Shall lure it back to cancel Half a Line,<br/>Nor all your Tears wash out a Word of it.&quot;<br/><br/>Yadda yadda.<br/><br/>__________<br/><br/>Incidntally, Omar Khayyam was a great Persian mathematician. &quot;Omar&quot; is a Sunni </span>
  <span id="freeText7063093206740765355" style="display:none">Some poetry snobs find these verses corny, with their psuedo-archaism of langauge and what nowadays would be called Orientalist romanticism.<br /><br />To Hell with all that. I've always liked them. In fact, I memorized most of it when I was a kid.<br /><br />"The moving Finger writes, and having writ, <br />Moves on, nor all your Piety nor Wit<br />Shall lure it back to cancel Half a Line,<br />Nor all your Tears wash out a Word of it."<br /><br />Yadda yadda.<br /><br />__________<br /><br />Incidntally, Omar Khayyam was a great Persian mathematician. "Omar" is a Sunni name, FWIW. I don't know when the Persians turned Shi'a.<br /><br />I don't know a lot of things.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7063093206740765355" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


